1.2 Analysis and Characterization of LTI Systems using the Laplace Transform

Causality

For a causal LTI system, the impulse response is zero for , and thus is right-sided. Therefore, the ROC associated with the system function for a causal system is a right-half plane.

For example, consider a system with impulse response

Since for all , this system is causal. Also, the system function can be obtained from previous examples as

In this case, the system function is rational and the ROC is to the right of the rightmost pole, consistent with our statement that causality for systems with rational system functions is equivalent to the ROC being to the right of the rightmost pole.

For one particular and very important class of systems, stability can be characterized very simply in terms of the locations of the poles. Specifically, consider a causal LTI system with a rational system function . Since the system is causal, the ROC is to the right of the rightmost pole. Consequently, for this system to be stable (i.e., for the ROC to include the -axis), the rightmost pole of must be to the left of the -axis, that is: a causal system with rational system function is stable iff. all of the poles of lie in the left-half of the -plane, i.e., all of the poles have negative real parts.
